WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Set here first.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Okay, we are rolling to David if you want to give us a slate.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:18.000
Okay.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:21.000
What first thing to say that you're on Channel 2?

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Okay.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
So this is David Cline.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
I'm on Channel 2.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I'll be talking today with Mr. Elmer Dixon, who is on Channel 1.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:35.000
We are in Seattle, Washington.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Today's date is February 28, 2013.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Again, this is David Cline for the Smithsonian and Mr. Elmer Dixon.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Great.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.000
We're rolling.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Okay.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
So I wanted to thank you very much again for meeting with me today.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:54.000
How's it going?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
I'm going to tell you a story.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And what I'd like to do is start by just having you talk a little bit about the family that you were raised in,

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.000
where they came how you ended up here in Seattle and what kind of home and values you were, feel that you were raised with.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Okay.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
My, both parents were originally from Chicago.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Actually, my father was from Kentucky, born in Kentucky, but moved to Chicago at a young age and was raised there.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:36.000
And my mother was raised in Chicago as well, but her parents had come up through the great southern migration from the South from Mississippi.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
And so they both of them had, well, my mother clearly, southern roots.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
My grandmother used to say that Kentucky's not the South.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:46.000
It's a border state.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:51.000
But as we know, it's got some southern aspects to it.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:02:05.000
But so I was born in Chicago and spent my early years between Chicago and Champaign, Illinois, where my father worked at an Air Force base.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:14.000
He actually was a World War II vet, but he was an illustrator who graduated from the Chicago Art Institute.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And so he worked on illustrating engineers' designs for aircraft or aircraft parts.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:33.000
And he eventually decided to move away from Illinois.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:44.000
I think he loved Chicago and the Chicago area, but he was an adventurer, some sort.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And part of that story is, of course, he wanted to get as far away from his mother-in-law.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:03:09.000
But so he got an opportunity to work at Boeing, and this would have been in 1957, and as an illustrator, and of course back then, there were no computer enhancements or computer drawings.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Everything was done by hand.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And that's what brought us to the Northwest.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:31.000
One of the things that I reflect on when I tell my story and my transition, I did a presentation in Lyon, France in 2010.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And it was at a conference with an organization called the Society for Intercultural Education Training and Research.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:50.000
And for the last 26 plus years, I've been doing work in the field of diversity and cross-cultural communication.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:59.000
And during that span of time, and I'll come back around to this, during that span of time, we have a lot of corporate clients.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:08.000
And so the identity, my identity as a panther, never was talked about or spoken about.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Only people in the Northwest who were clients, who knew of my past, knew that I was connected to the Black Panther Party.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
But our corporate clients, I mean, I've sat in offices with the CEO of PepsiCo and other major companies around the United States, and no one ever knew.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:34.000
But here was an opportunity at this particular, they call it a Congress, that SIETAR Europa holds every three to four years.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:48.000
At this particular SIETAR Europa in France, the theme of their conference was human rights and cultural diversity, where to draw the line.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And I saw that as a perfect opportunity to talk about that topic, because of my own experiences as a member of the Black Panther Party, and also as an interculturalist through the work that I do.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.000
And so, in fact, my speech was titled from Revolutionary to Interculturalist.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:26.000
But I think that's kind of an interesting concept, as I've thought about it, because I actually probably began my early life in some ways as an interculturalist and never knew it, never realized it at the time.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And that was because of the values that our parents instilled in us, but also the environment that we grew up in.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:44.000
In Chicago, we lived on the south side. I stayed with my grandmother, on my mother's side of the family, for a couple of years as a young toddler.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:52.000
But on the south side of Chicago, then as today, it's largely a segregated community, largely Black.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And in Champagne, well, I don't remember much about the neighborhood in Champagne, I know we were in a housing project there.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:16.000
And I don't remember too many different color friends at that young age. I don't know if I would have noticed, but I knew that looking back, I know that in Chicago, on the south side, it was a predominantly Black community.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:27.000
When we moved to Seattle, and it took us a couple of years to settle in the home that our mother still lives in in Madrona.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:34.000
We moved in that home in 1960, and as a 10-year-old, moving into this neighborhood in Madrona.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:46.000
It was like landing in the proverbial melting pot, if you will. I don't like to refer to the U.S. as a melting pot, more like a salad bowl rather than a melting pot.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:59.000
But that was the neighborhood in which we landed. And it was a neighborhood that had been maybe 30, 40 years earlier, a predominantly white neighborhood, a Jewish neighborhood.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:10.000
There were synagogues in the area. And what happened as happened in most inner cities as blacks moved in, whites would move out.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:25.000
But in this particular neighborhood, a little bit of everyone moved in. And so on the playground, which is across the street from our home that we grew up in, it was the gathering place.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And I tell you, you could go on that playground and interact with white kids who were average income, rich kids, rich white kids, who lived across the red zone line, which happened to be two blocks from our home.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:08:00.000
We didn't know it at the time, the red lining district. And there was Chinese, there were Japanese, there were Filipino, there were Latino, Mexican-American. It was just everybody was there. And black, of course.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And while it was, I think, largely black, it had, you know, I said me percentage wise, but everybody else was there as well. And so that was the environment in which we grew up in and the schools that we attended.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:43.000
But the other side of that was the influences that our parents had on us. And while they had grown up, or gone through life, their adult life and early life with some consciousness of what was going on in America, I don't know how you could be unconscious to it in the 40s, 50s, 60s.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:09:06.000
My father, when he was, I think he was in high school at the time, or just graduated when Pearl Harbor was bombed. And he and his buddies who had formed a, and they may have been in their first year of college, had formed a group called the Four Feathers that was named after the Four Feathers at Notre Dame.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And they actually had sweaters, which my mom still has the sweater today with the feather on it and the number four on it. And they were a tight knit group. They all went out and they volunteered for the draft because they wanted to fight and defend their country.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:35.000
And when they were able to, these are for black men. And they were able to get through the induction process. And they were assigned their orders to go to the office.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:47.000
They had some city on there that they didn't know where it was. And I think it said, MS at the end, and they were thinking they were going to Massachusetts to some place.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:10:01.000
Well, as it turned out, they were going to Mississippi. And so when they got down there, of course, and segregated living quarters, segregated camp, if you will.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And they would drill and go through the regular rigors of boot camp in preparation for preparing to fight at some point. And on probably more than one occasion, as my father recounted these stories, if you kind of remember any of the old movies where soldiers are marching off to fight in this big war, they called World War II the big one.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And the confetti would be flying and people would be standing on the side of the street waving flags and cheering them on as they got ready to go out and defend America.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:50.000
And so when they walked through this Mississippi town, they weren't greeted by confetti and flags. They were greeted by crowds that were booing and hissing at them and spitting and throwing things and calling them nigger.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:11:06.000
And it was, I'm sure my father wasn't oblivious to this, but it was kind of a rude awakening in 1942 or 43 whenever that was that they were getting ready to go put their lives on a line to defend America.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:17.000
We had this strong sense of pride and patriotism to go defend the United States after the attack on Pearl Harbor and to be treated like that.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:26.000
But those and other incidents that occurred, my mother had her fair share of incidents about her color.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:39.000
Those things never colored their perception of other people. It never left them with a negative sense of who other people were or are.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And so we always learned to, as Dr. King used to say, judge people by the content of their character and not the color of their skin.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And I think that that was one of the principal values that we grew up with that was so strong in our household.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:13.000
And so I remember during those early years and as we were developing and living in this environment that my father had a fierce protective sense about his family and about his kids.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And I remember on one occasion, I had two very close friends out of all of these people that kids that I met, I tended to be an outgoing kid.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:34.000
And on our block there was a black family that was large, that was at the end of our street.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:43.000
There was a white family next door to them. In fact, everybody in the neighborhood called the woman Aunt Barbara.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:49.000
So she was like, you know, the anti, you know, you always hear about anti. She was a white woman.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And then her son, actually, I think it was maybe her, either her grandson or stepson was a good friend of ours.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:08.000
But my two best friends were two young white guys who I had met through school and we used to hang out a lot.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:17.000
But we always used to get our mischief as well. And I remember we used to go and get eggs from the local store and go throw them at passing cars.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:26.000
And one evening we were out tossing eggs and Aaron was with my brother Aaron was with us at the time.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And everybody had tossed the eggs and took off. And we missed the car.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And so I wasn't leaving. I was determined to land my egg.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:47.000
And the car came through. I didn't notice it was the same car that had barely gotten missed before.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And I launched my egg and as it hit, the car stopped. The guy got out and ran up and grabbed me.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And I don't think he met any real ill. I think he was trying to scold me and telling me that was not right or whatever.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:14.000
But here I was 11 or 12 years old. And I was petrified and mad and struggling and got away.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And it was more than a block from our home. And ran to the house and burst through the door and told my father this man was attacking me.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:34.000
And he grabbed the nearest thing he could grab a hammer or whatever and took right out the door and told him that no one was going to attack his kid.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:41.000
But that was that fierce protection of your family was one thing that we learned.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And so on any given weekend, my parents would have guests over.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:57.000
And on one weekend, they might have one of their black friends over a black couple and they would sit down and listen to Ellington and Count Basie.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:05.000
And we grew up with a lot of music in our house. And then on other occasions, there would be different people that would come over.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:12.000
And I remember on Saturday mornings, many times that we would get up and it was wax the floor days.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:21.000
And my mother still lives in this big house. It's a big huge four bedroom house built around the turn of the 20th century, like in 1908.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:31.000
It's a very sturdy big home. And we would have to roll back the push back the furniture, roll up the carpets and on our hands and knees the boys, not my sister.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.000
She got off of that duty. We had to get on.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:42.000
And have any other in your house? There's four of us. And she's the oldest and then the three boys. And I'm the middle son.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:52.000
And so we had to get on our hands and knees and wax these hardwood floors to a high luster.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:16:04.000
And while we were doing so, my father would have plain on the high fai, La Bohème, Madame Butterfly,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:18.000
the Tales of Hoffmann, So we learned an appreciation for opera at a very young age. And so it was a full range of appreciation of different kinds of music.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:27.000
That was again that kind of broad, kind of cultural overlay. But we found out later why we had to polish the floors.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:41.000
Because on certain nights of the month, he would invite his Scandinavian friends over. And they were from various parts of Scandinavian lived in various parts of the city.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:51.000
But they were all white. A couple of them were Jewish. And they would come in and they would do these loud Scandinavian dancers dancing on the floor.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:17:06.000
And then you can hear the wooden floors just rocking with these dances, these Scandinavian dances. And so when I think about the cross-cultural experiences that we had as kids,

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:17.000
we would go over some of the Jewish friends homes on Easter, actually on their Passover. And I ate my first matzeball when I was probably 11 years old

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:27.000
and gained a high appreciation and liking for Jewish culture, and especially the eating of the festive food that they ate.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:35.000
And they would come over and maybe share an Easter dinner with us. There was almost like a cultural exchange that was going on there.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:48.000
And on other occasions, the two of the two white friends that I mentioned, one was his mother, was a second generation. I believe she was second generation Russian.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:18:04.000
I know her mother was first generation, her grandmother. And so I would go over their house on Christmas celebrations. And they were Orthodox Christians. And they ate certain kind of foods that were very unique to that Russian culture.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:11.000
And so it was a pretty interesting experience growing up in that neighborhood.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:40.000
Chinese immigrants. And they were very well known in the community. And I remember once after one of my friends taught me how to steal.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:51.000
I was nervous as heck. You were asking me whether I would get nervous. I don't get nervous talking. But I remember when I was trying to steal this one candy bar, I was probably so nervous.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:19:06.000
Because it was outside of my, what I believed what should do. But he said, now you can do it. Get it. And may caught me. And for the next, I think 20 years, she called me bad boy.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:24.000
But she would joke about it in later years. But it was a close relationship that everyone had in that neighborhood. And as I said, we came from so many different cultural backgrounds. It was an important development in our lives.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.000
And eventually in mine in terms of this full circle in terms of the work that I do today.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:46.000
I was going to ask for your father at Boeing, which I imagined wasn't a arts league African-American workforce.

00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:58.000
I imagine he hadn't navigated that world as well.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:15.000
There's, you know, we talk about influences there are several things that I pulled from my experience growing up with my parents. And one of the things that I, two of the things that I got from my father was his outgoingness.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:34.000
So everybody loved him and he could make friends like in a minute. He was very, I guess charismatic as one way to put it. But he was very smooth. He was easy to get along with.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And so he made friends very quickly at Boeing. In fact, many of those people are, I suppose that he met many of them at Boeing. I'm sure all of them did not work at Boeing. He had to meet them in some other connection.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:21:06.000
I know that he had some connection with some of the civil rights organizations as well as I think even there may have been kind of the taboo back then the commonist party members.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:26.000
I don't know to what degree he interacted with those folks, but all of those people that I mentioned who I've known through adulthood have all had very progressive.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:43.000
So he was a very outgoing person and that was one of the things that I absorbed from his personality. The other thing was the adventurism. He was always looking to find some adventure in life.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:59.000
I remember there was a program on TV back when we were growing up called Adventures in Paradise (1959-62 ABC TV series); Kon-Tiki raft. And this ship called Adventures in Paradise (1959-62 ABC TV series); Kon-Tiki raft would sail around the world and stop in exotic places.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:06.000
He had been stationed in Hawaii during his tour. He ended up in...

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:51.000
I think what it resulted in for me personally was a kind of a can-do attitude which would come into play initially when I got into the Black Panther Party and later in life as I embarked on my own personal life.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:23:01.000
Because as a member of the Black Panther Party we were all in for the community and we didn't have any selfish desires or individual desires at that point.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:24:08.000
I remember the TV and kind of mimicking the soldiers as they were marching along with his coffin and seeing Ruby assassinated on live TV, not Ruby but Oswald being assassinated on live TV.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:19.000
I remember Medgar Evers being shot. I remember the bombing of the...

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:36.000
You know, on Nightly TV it seemed like we had a routine of course as I think many families did then and maybe today still where when we got home we had to finish our homework before we could go out to the park or go do something.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:47.000
The homework was done. Dinner was on the table at 6 o'clock and we had to be there at the table. It was important to my father that we eat around the table together as a family. We did that every night.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:25:01.000
Then after dinner was over, Worsh had dishes, you know, put them away because everybody had a routine. In fact that same routine when I was raising my family. Someone washed, someone dried and someone put them away.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:28.000
After that was done, then there was time to watch TV. I remember on the Nightly evening new spots, seeing the incidents like the bloody Sunday on the Edmund Pettus Bridge and demonstrators being beaten by police and hosed by firefighters and beaten by police dogs.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:43.000
I remember when I was in prison, there were very vivid scenes and I think it was painful for me and that I was a young boy growing up who...

00:25:43.000 --> 00:26:02.000
I had aspirations of being a doctor. I think that a lot of kids relate to people that kind of protect the community. Being a police officer or a firefighter was a position that you looked at with respect.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:21.000
I had seen that dichotomy with these protectors of society being brutal and being the opposite of what you would expect was an interesting way to view how things were shaking out in our real world.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:40.000
I didn't realize that at the time but those things would become part of my psyche and part of my growth and development. One of my colleagues that I work with today talks about the effects of racism and he says that it's not a single incident.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:27:05.000
Sometimes people ask you, so when have you been discriminated against or what has happened to you and it's not a single incident. He calls it a series of micro abrasions. When you have a wound or a sore and it scabs over and you keep picking at the scab because it's bothering you, that over time it's like this wound that never goes away.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:24.000
He compares the experience of racism and oppression and all of the things that have occurred not only to blocks with other people that have been oppressed as this series of micro abrasions.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:34.000
I saw these things, they were having some impact but I didn't realize just how so.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:45.000
It was in the summer of I believe 1967. It was either 67 or 66.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:47.000
What were you born?

00:27:47.000 --> 00:28:05.000
I was born in 1950. So I was a 16 year old or 17 year old at the time. That my brother Aaron being a year older than me was his awareness point actually happened before mine.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:28.000
We would talk about these occurrences but I wasn't fully into this awareness piece yet. It was also an interesting time because in the mid 60s the black awareness movement was happening and it hadn't hit me yet.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:42.000
I think it hit our city at 65. I was still skateboarding with my two very close white friends where we would go up to Crater Lake which is the second deepest lake in the world.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:51.000
We went up there with his parents, his mother and siblings and we got on our skateboards and skateboarded down. That was in 65.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:29:00.000
I was at 15 year olds at the time and I hadn't gotten into awareness of who I was as a black person.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:10.000
My brother, like I said, 67 or 66 or 67, invited or told me that I needed to go hear the speaker that was coming to Garfield High School.

00:29:10.000 --> 00:29:19.000
The speaker's name was Stokely Carmichael. I didn't know much about Stokely Carmichael. I had heard a little bit, Aaron and I had talked a little bit.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:34.000
I didn't know that I was aware of the Watts rebellions and the Detroit rebellions. It's an interesting thing. Of course people refer to them as riots, watch riots and the Detroit riots.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:52.000
There was a well-known musician and writer who wrote several high-profile R&B songs that were successful in the charts.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:30:13.000
The writer, the songwriter, was white. After the Watts and Detroit rebellions, he wrote an essay in which he said that the rebellions in Detroit and Watts were a natural response to the conditions in which those people lived.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:26.000
Because of that, he was blacklisted. He didn't get any record contracts for another 10, 15 years. I was aware of those things. It hadn't meshed for me at all of those things that were occurring.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:42.000
I went to hear Stokely Carmichael. I remember vividly the things that Stokely Carmichael was talking about. One of the things I remember him saying was that the problem with the black community is that he was not a black person.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:49.000
The black community is black people who don't love themselves. He said, you hate the color of your skin and you want to be white.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:31:06.000
He said, look at how you've been programmed. When you go to a movie theater and you see the good night and the bad night, why is the good night always on a white horse and the bad night always on a black horse?

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:18.000
When you turn on your TV and you look at a western, why is the good cowboy dressed in white, wears a 10 gallon hat and rides a horse named Trigger and a white horse named Trigger.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:31.000
The bad cowboy is named Dirty Bart and he's in black clothes and on a black horse. He said, even when you go sit down and eat food, you order cake, dessert, angel food cake is white and devil food cake is black.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:38.000
He made all of these analogies and I was thinking, that has nothing to do with anything. I don't hate the fact that I'm black.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:55.000
After I'd left that rally and I was sitting on the playground, I remember sitting on the tennis courts and the tennis courts are right at the playground and the tennis courts are right across the street from our house.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:05.000
During the summer months, when our parents were at work, we would go to the playground and either play here, play in the community center or play tennis.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:14.000
I began to think about what he had said and think about some of the occurrences in my own life.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:33.000
I remember thinking about our tennis team because here we were a tennis team that was predominantly black and an instructor who came to teach us the final point of the game. Her name was Miss Sullivan.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:50.000
She came as a volunteer or a worker who came to the park department and I think she was either a student at the University of Washington or was recently graduated from there.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:59.000
She taught us the finer points about tennis and everybody loved Miss Sullivan. She was cute too.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:08.000
That year we had won all of our tournaments and won the right to go play for the City Championship.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:23.000
The City Championship was being held not 15-20 blocks from our house across the red line which we didn't know existed but down on the lake at the Seattle Tennis Club.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:46.000
We got on our tennis whites and our little shirts that said Madrona on it and when she got us down into the tennis club and we were sitting in the cafeteria waiting for our turn to go out on the tennis court and in walked this tall black man in kitchen whites.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:56.000
He looked at us black kids sitting there and he said, what are you doing in here? You better get back there and get your clothes on and get the work.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:02.000
He thought we were the help, some hired help for maybe an event that they were having.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:10.000
As it turned out, of course, they didn't allow blacks in the tennis club. We didn't know that.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:20.000
We were here to play tennis and he thought we were joking. We actually went out and beat the other team which happened to be a white team.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:31.000
The tennis club along with some park department officials, I can't believe they were park department officials that would have done this.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:39.000
They had the tennis club at the Seattle Tennis Club. Left before giving us our trophies.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:48.000
They didn't have a trophy presentation. We suppose they have a trophy presentation out on the court and they left before and didn't give us our trophies.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:58.000
We were in their all white tennis club. I remember thinking about that and thinking about my, you know, a few other things that occurred.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:07.000
My mother when we moved here and she had gone for an interview for a job. She had found in the newspaper. When she got there, they told her that the position was filled.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:12.000
She said, well, I just saw it and the paper said, but yeah, we filled it since then. She had called down to see if it was still open.

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:20.000
She went back and I don't know if she went to a phone booth or whatever and she called them again and said, I'm inquiring about this position.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:28.000
They said, oh, sure, come down and we'd like you to apply. I remember hearing those things and observing these things.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:38.000
All the while, you know, there was my friends who were white, the pastor at our church who was white, I had a good relationship with people.

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:49.000
I wasn't about black and white and I thought to myself, I don't want to be white. I like who I am.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:59.000
But sometimes I maybe wished that I had some of the things that they had. You see my two white friends who lived on the other side of the red line.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:09.000
They lived in the neighborhood just two blocks away. It was upscale. One of them, in fact, even had a maid.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:15.000
And their maid's name was Hazel. It used to be a 1960s show.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:26.000
And as I thought, you know, I wanted the things that they had, which were nicer than mine, but I don't want to be white, I don't think.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:38.000
But that's kind of where the awareness of my own skin color and the fact that I needed to be prideful in it began.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
So did Stoke these words kind of rattle around?

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:49.000
Stoke these words rattle around. And so my brother and I knew that we had to be involved. He had already become...

00:36:49.000 --> 00:37:01.000
This was now in the fall of 67. He had started at the University of Washington and was in the Black Student Union with perhaps one of the other people you may be interviewing Larry Gossett.

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:17.000
And I was now a senior going into high school and I had actually joined SNCC and was appointed the co-chair of the Seattle chapter of SNCC.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:40.000
And we would try to do some community organizing, but most of the organizing was around voter registration. That was one of the big things during the civil rights movement was registering Black people to vote because of the conditions in the South really kind of pushed this civil rights movement across the United States.

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:49.000
So we did some of the same things that they were doing in one of those voter registration, but we felt like we didn't have much direction.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:38:04.000
And we were contemplating how can we make an impact? And I was politicized by then. I was aware of who I was and I was becoming politically aware and standing up.

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:16.000
And in fact, I along with four or five of my closest friends at Garfield decided that we were going to have a Black Student Union at Garfield.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:32.000
And with all kinds of opposition, of course, when we went to the principal with our idea, he said, no, you can't have a Black Student Union. You don't need one. You have a boys club.

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:50.000
Of course, boys was a derogatory term back then, which in fact, to credit of one of my, who's deceased, not one of my classmates, who was a student body president, got the name changed to the Garfield men's club.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:39:02.000
But we said, yeah, but that's for the whole student body. We need something to speak for the rights of Black students. And he said, no, we're not going to do that.

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:10.000
And so we were adamant that we were going to have a Black Student Union. And so we did several kind of things to agitate our.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:22.000
I was in the, what they call the stage band and the jazz band. I learned to play trumpet and all of his kids had picked up an instrument.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:35.000
But I probably was, I was the one that stayed with mine the longest. I was in the marching band. I was the drum major of the band. I was in the concert band, both in junior high and into high school.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:42.000
I was in kind of now the elite band, which was the jazz band. And they called it the stage band because we got to play at the Pep rallies.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:53.000
And so one of the things that I, as I became politicized when the Pledge of Allegiance was, you know, said every morning, I wouldn't stand up for the Pledge of Allegiance.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:40:05.000
When we had to play at the Pep rallies to play the star-spangled banner at the start of the Pep rally, I would sit down and play the star-spangled banner.

00:40:05.000 --> 00:40:11.000
I got kicked out of school on a couple of occasions because I wouldn't adhere to, you know, the rules.

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:23.000
And on one morning we decided, well, we're going to, you know, throw off this Pep rally to gain recognition.

00:40:23.000 --> 00:40:33.000
And we did this chant where I would start and then they would echo in the stand. And it went something like Bing, Bing, Bang, Bang, Ungawa, Black Power.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:43.000
So people would echo what we said. And then when we did that, the whole student body just erupted. Everybody, you know, Black students, white students, all of them just erupted.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:51.000
And so I got kicked out of school for that. But then, so we decided, we were kind of putting a pressure on. We decided, well, we're going to call a boycott.

00:40:51.000 --> 00:41:00.000
And we told the principal, if you don't give us a BSU, we're going to boycott classes. He said, ah, yeah, well, it'll only be you and your friends. And then we'll expel you again.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:13.000
And so what he didn't realize was that for most of those white students, the Asian students, the Latino students, we'd all gone to school together through grit from grade school on up.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:22.000
And these were most of them were our friends. They were, you know, and so when we called, and plus I was the drum major of the marching band, everybody in school knew who I was.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:35.000
And so when we called the boycott, the only people that went to class were the honor students. And the hallway and Garfield filled up in front of the principal's office.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:48.000
No one was going to class. And the principal sent out his messenger and they relented. We got a black student union and we were the first, actually the first high school black student union on the west coast.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:42:09.000
And, and so I was becoming more now kind of aware of not only my own self and having developed in a political consciousness, but there was a few incidents that were kind of projecting me into a leadership role.

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:26.000
And there was a couple of minor scrapes, you know, I'd never been arrested before. I remember coming back from a high school basketball game, which I played. I had my trumpet with me.

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:34.000
And I went down to one of the local spots for teens gathered, which had to be in fact in front of a rival high school, Franklin high school.

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:50.000
And there was a, it was like a big riot going on. I kind of landed in the middle of a riot. And I didn't realize what was happening, but I got out anyway to see why you know police were throwing tear gas and dispersing kids.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:58.000
And there was this one black girl that I knew Deborah Rodriguez, who was being pinned to the ground by two officers.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:12.000
And I was asking her, you know, are you all right? What's, what's, you know, you know, get your knee off of her back. And the next thing I knew I was being, you know, whisked away handcuffed and taken off.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:17.000
And to, to juvenile and I was charged with inciting a riot.

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:31.000
Because I was speaking out, you know, against this, this young black woman being, you know, brutalized by these cops. And, and I went before the judge, you know, I wouldn't relent.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:41.000
But what he said was, you know, I'm not going to send you any time, but I'd like you to write an essay on why you thought it was important to defend that, that young woman.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:51.000
And so I did around this same time, there was a few incidents happening at that high school, Franklin high school.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:44:01.000
There were, there had been a fight between four students. And Franklin was almost as, about as diverse as Garfield.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:13.000
And this fight between two white students had nothing to do with race. But the two white students were sent back to class. The two black students were expelled.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:30.000
The, there was a young black woman who showed up one day with an afro. And the principal, she was sent to the principal's offices. And she was told to, she could not, she was expelled from school and told she could come back to school when she had an appropriate hairdo.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:44.000
And that was kind of the last straw. And the students at Franklin, the black students there wanted to organize and one of the, one to get this young woman reinstated in the school and they wanted the black student union.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:59.000
And of course, they had gotten the same answer that we had gotten. So they, they, they called Larry, who was at the UW and called me at Garfield. And so several of us at Garfield and, and the UW, including my brother Aaron,

00:44:59.000 --> 00:45:16.000
came to Franklin, met with the students and then we walked across the street and walked into the principal's office and took over the principal's office and had a sit in in his office and told him we were taken over his office until they addressed these concerns and gave the, gave the students some representation through a black student union.

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:28.000
They fled the office and we ended up staying in the building overnight. The next morning, the phone rang and you know we were, we were doing business. We answered the phone. Good morning, Franklin, high school, you know.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:41.000
And it was the administration and they said, look, you can have, well, we'll address these demands. You'll have the, they'll get a BSU. Please leave our, our building. So we left the building.

00:45:41.000 --> 00:46:04.000
And it was about a week later. I was in my geometry class at Garfield and the phone rang and Mr. Nairamor said that they, someone in the office wants you in the office, which wasn't unusual. I had been called to the office on the number of patients.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:19.000
So I stepped outside of the office and in the hallway were two detectives who read me my rights and handcuffed me and proceeded to escort me out of the school.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:42.000
And I was arrested for unlawful assembly and unbeknownst to me at the time. My brother Aaron, Larry Gossett and several other leaders both at the UW and at the two high schools were being arrested almost simultaneously.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:47:08.000
And within within the hour, it had to be within the hour or so. King was assassinated. And one, we knew that they had gotten us off of the street because they wanted to get leaders potentially that could cause, you know, you know, some confusion for them off of the street.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:20.000
So all of the leaders of the, you know, the radical leaders they had gotten the black radical leaders they had gotten and put us in jail. I was in juvenile because I was underage. And I remember being in juvenile and seeing.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:23.000
What did they charge you at unlawful assembly?

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:48.000
From the Franklin incident. And I remember seeing the, you know, the cities burning across the U.S. and James Brown was, was, was in D.C., and they had been trying to do a concert. He was trying to tell people, you know, don't go out and burn your neighborhoods. He was exhorting people not to, you know, to ride and not to burn, but, you know, to no avail.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:48:03.000
People were mad. And my parents, when they came to pick me up that evening, that night to, to get me out of juvenile, they had realized that both of their sons were in jail now, the two older sons.

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:14.000
And when they picked me up, the only thing they said to me was, are you all right? And then we drove home in silence.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:29.000
And, you know, the feeling was, you know, palpable, palpable, you know, in terms of their, them being distraught over the assassination of King on the one hand.

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:43.000
And the fact that their two sons were in jail that same day, it was as if they knew something was going to change in their, in their, in their lives and in their, in their sons lives.

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:53.000
Do you remember talking with them about, I mean, you're talking about how your own consciousness is, whether you were having these conversations with your, with your folks.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:08.000
Yeah, well, the whole cross cultural experience, I think, was, was kind of an unspoken thing, you know, I think they had put us in the environment. And so, and as I said, I, I wasn't aware of, I thought that's the way life was supposed to be.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:21.000
And so, I was in aware of, of what its impact was on me growing up. I think the, when I was becoming aware, I don't remember having the conversation with them.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:30.000
You know, I think that, like I said, when we went in March with King and, and my father said, you know, we're going to go to this March and we thought that was important because he said it was.

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:42.000
And we knew that we had seen stuff on TV and, and they had talked, we had talked about probably the, you know, the, the, the, you know, the, the, the Sunday and the bombing of the, the, the, the, you know, the church.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:55.000
And we talked about those, those kind of things. But in terms of my own personal, you know, it wasn't like they were directing me and, you know, trying and observing the, you know, this progression. These were things that were happening in internal.

00:49:55.000 --> 00:50:05.000
And, and so, you know, I didn't discuss, you know, I mean, they were obviously were aware when I was arrested the first time for the inside of the riot.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:20.000
And I had been interviewed by a, a newspaper. In fact, I'll show you the clip here after we're done when I was 17. And then right in the middle of that. And you could see my Afro.

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:49.000
I had the SNCC jacket on and they were asking me about the Vietnam War. And, you know, my words to them was they were asking if I thought it was a more worth fighting in and I, my response. And they had asked several students. And I was one of several students that put in this newspaper article that, you know, that, that World War II was something, you know, where people were fighting for something that was a word they could.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:51:05.000
And I was a worthy cause. We knew why we were in it. We knew that we were defending ourselves after Pearl Harbor was bombed while I didn't really fully understand, you know, the full implications of what the Japanese were faced with. And this whole imperialist thing, I wasn't fully aware and breast of that.

00:51:05.000 --> 00:51:14.000
But I knew that, you know, from my father, my father's fighting in the war is patriotic response. That that was a natural patriotic response.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:30.000
But that here we were fighting, you know, an alleged enemy, you know, 15,000 miles away from the United States that had never attacked us and had never, you know, shown any aggression towards the United States.

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:41.000
And so my response was that, no, this is not something that I think that people should be fighting for. And so I was, these were things that, and my parents saw the article in these papers.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:52.000
And I knew they had to know that I was developing a political consciousness. And I'm sure that I probably, you know, mild off some things, whether I don't remember sitting down and having this conversation.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:52:02.000
But it was at this point where things were, they knew that the, they knew that some sort of development was happening with their son.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:13.000
And so I think that, because we were both arrested at this, at the, on the same day the king was assassinated in association with this event at Franklin High School.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:31.000
And it was about a week later, because we were already Aaron and I and a group of people from Seattle, BSU students were already lined up to go to the West Coast Conference for Black Student Union in San Francisco.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:46.000
San Francisco State University. And Aaron and I had been talking much more about political organizing. And we actually had gotten a hold of a paper, a Black Panther newspaper.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:57.000
And so we were aware that the Black Panther Party existed and had some rough idea of who they were. But we didn't fully understand what they represented.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:06.000
But we knew that they were, you know, like developing into a powerful voice, at least in California, because the Black Panther Party started in 1966.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:21.000
It was not a national organization in 67 or 68, not yet. And here we were in the spring of 1968. And we traveled to San Francisco.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:40.000
And we had gotten wind that the day before Martin Luther King was assassinated, a young Black Panther by the name of Bobby Hutton had been assassinated and shot by Oakland police.

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:52.000
And they were having his funeral that weekend. And a few of us said, well, you know, we're going over to show our support.

00:53:52.000 --> 00:54:01.000
And that Saturday, we left the conference early and drove across the Bay Bridge into West Oakland.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:19.000
And I remember, you know, I can still see the scene vividly in my mind today. When we got down into, on the street level in West Oakland, you started seeing large groups of Black people gathering.

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:34.000
Some of them, there was one big gathering in a park or in some area. You had Panthers, both men and women in leather jackets and berets lined up in like platoon formation.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:44.000
And I remember seeing that and thinking, my God, this looks like a Black Army. And we had to get out, of course, blocks away from the church in order to find parking.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:55:02.000
And we were walking through, you know, this scene. And everybody had on leather jackets and berets and black slacks and I remember seeing a group of people talking off to one side.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:10.000
And there were whites in this group. And one of them was Marlon Brando. I recognized Marlon Brando. He was talking to who I would later find out that was Bobby Seale.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:15.000
And when they both...

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:25.000
Can you remember, yeah, I'm sorry to interrupt, but your reaction to seeing what you described as the Black Army. What was it like to see?

00:55:25.000 --> 00:55:47.000
It was overwhelming. It was both a... It was kind of like a culmination of this discovering who I was as a young Black man and having a consciousness and an identity.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:56:10.000
But seeing a group that looked organized and ready to defend their community. It was very a stark contrast to the images that I saw on TV with the singing demonstrators walking arm and arm, you know, singing We Shall Overcome.

00:56:10.000 --> 00:56:32.000
Because this looked like someone, a group of revolutionaries who weren't talking about We Shall Overcome, they looked like they were ready to take what was rightfully theirs in terms of their human dignity and their rights and protect their community.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:45.000
And so it was a sense of pride, of defiance. It was almost an overwhelming sense of, you know, this is where I belong. This is who I am.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:57:06.000
And when we got inside the church to view the body of Bobby Hutton, when we stepped into the church, lining the walls all the way around where young Black man and women in Afros and Berets and shotguns and bandoleros.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:19.000
And the casket was draped in a Black Panther flag. And all of these images, you know, were like it was just a shock, you know.

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:33.000
And I remember walking by the coffin and I had heard that, you know, in conversation on the way there that Bobby Hutton had been hit by 30 police bullets.

00:57:33.000 --> 00:57:43.000
And the reason why Dolly Hutton, wanted the coffin to be open, that's what people could see what the police had done to her son.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:53.000
And I remember when I was filing Bobby's little Bobby's coffin and seeing him in there, he was 17 years old. And I was 17 years old.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:58:06.000
And I remember thinking that, you know, that could be me laying there. And I think that was the moment for me where I said, that's it. You know, this is who I am and there is no turning back.

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:14.000
And you know, people often ask me about that era in my life and that period and ask me if I was afraid. There was never any fear.

00:58:14.000 --> 00:58:27.000
I was afraid to, I can't speak for other people, but there was never a fear about putting my life on the line or giving my life to the revolution, so to speak.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:43.000
It was a defiance and an indignant response to the racism and the racist brutality that the power structuring the United States had inflicted upon not only Black people, but people, you know, people that did that.

00:58:43.000 --> 00:59:10.000
You know, people that didn't have means whether we're poor whites, whether it be Native Americans, whether it be farm workers, you know, immigrant populations, anyone who was different from the status quo, it was like this immense indignant, indignant response to this, this, this overwhelming oppression and dehumanizing of a people.

00:59:10.000 --> 00:59:27.000
And so that all kind of jelled for me in that moment and I'm sure for many of us as we headed back to the conference, we knew that Bobby Seale was scheduled to speak that night at the BSU conference.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:40.000
And we waited for him to speak and he showed up with his bodyguards and several Panthers and he gave probably the most fiery speech that I had ever heard.

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:56.000
And after his speech, you were either afraid because it was like a line was being drawn in the sand or you were destined to become a panther around the revolution.

00:59:56.000 --> 01:00:15.000
And so a small group of us, Aaron, myself, two or three others, not the whole contingent that came with from Seattle, but a few of us went over and cornered Bobby and said we wanted to start a chapter of the Black Panther Party in Seattle.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:29.000
And he told us to go ahead and finish this conference and return to Seattle and that within two weeks he would be there and he would outline for us what we needed to do to organize the chapter.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:46.000
We set that up when his arrival would be and the day that he came there were probably 50 potential Panthers in my parents' home.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:49.000
How did you put the word up?

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:59.000
I went out through the grapevine, the community has a grapevine. And it was, you know, 50 was a small core group at that time.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:18.000
And when my parents came home from work, all these bodies were laying on the floor and listening to Bobby talk and they just came in, stepped over everyone, you know, stepped around and went straight back into the kitchen which was usually the gathering place, closed the door and left us alone.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:39.000
See, because they knew something was coming and this was the something. And we organized the chapter. Aaron, my brother was, you know, given the leadership, he was the defense captain.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:53.000
I was a field lieutenant and we had a few other positions in there and that began the journey. We were the first chapter to be organized outside of the state of California.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:02:11.000
And from that beginning, the chapters of the Black Panther Party spread like wildfire across the United States until we had a chapter and just about every one of the contiguous 48 states.

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:20.000
What did, I'm curious what Bobby Seale said to you it meant to be a Panther and whether that changed for you over time.

01:02:20.000 --> 01:02:31.000
Well, you know, it was it was pretty clear to us early on as we were trying to figure out, you know, you know, how we were going to organize and and of course it, you know, it had to evolve.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:41.000
But it was it was clear to us for most of us that we were committed. We were we were in a lifelong struggle.

01:02:41.000 --> 01:02:49.000
He ran down the the 10 point program of the Black Panther Party.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:03:05.000
Can you just tell us what that is, the 10 point program? Can you pause for one second? Sure. Are we back on? We are. The interesting thing is that you were talking about, you know, what it meant to be a member of the Black Panther Party.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:20.000
And most of us who were younger than 20 at the time because I was 17, my brother would have been 19.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:30.000
He's about a year and six months older than me. And many of us were around that age group 18, 19, 20, 17.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:46.000
Most of us who were serious, we either knew that we would be dead before we were 25. And those of us that that accepted that reality didn't care.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:59.000
Those of those that looked at it and knew that if they stayed in the party, they would be dead by 25. They probably were out of the organization within six months because they weren't willing to go to that that extent.

01:03:59.000 --> 01:04:11.000
And so what it meant was you had to be willing. You had to know what it meant to be a Panther, the fact that you would be probably in the line of fire now.

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:19.000
Because it was in 1968 that very year that J. Edgar Hoover claimed that the Black Panther Party was the number one threat to the internal security of the United States.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:38.000
That's a pretty strong designation. That's like that's how they talk about Al Qaeda today. So if you put that in retrospect to 1968 and the party being named the number one threat to the internal security of the United States, that meant we had a bull's eye on us.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:50.000
And so as we it was important for us to understand what it meant to be a Panther as you said, how did Bobby communicate that?

01:04:50.000 --> 01:05:07.000
Because in the early days of the Black Panther Party, and I presume that you will end up interviewing Bobby Seale for this program, the party had organized around

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:21.000
a couple of basic principles. One was that people had a right to live a life and pursue the American dream without being shot and killed and brutalized in their communities.

01:05:21.000 --> 01:05:33.000
And we didn't organize around civil rights, but we organized around what we believed were God-given rights. And the right to humanity and dignity was one of them.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:50.000
And when Huey and Bobby decided that they were going to form the Black Panther Party, they took the name from another organization that had the Panther as a symbol. They were the Lowndes County Freedom Organization.

01:05:50.000 --> 01:06:09.000
And they had the symbol of the Black Panther because the Black Panther by nature is a defensive animal. And so we, not an aggressor. So we didn't form initially to be the aggressor, but to take a defensive posture.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:38.000
And in fact, the first name of the Black Panther Party was the Black Panther Party for self-defense. And so what had happened during those early years in 66 and 67, the first program that the Panther Party organized, we call them survival programs, was the police alert patrol because that was an immediate need in Black communities across the United States, was the end, the racist brutality by cops committed against Black Americans.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:46.000
And so we had a committed against Black people, which is one of the points in the 10 point program. And I'll talk about the 10 point program in a minute.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:07:01.000
But when, in order to get that point across, Huey used to teach us that power is the ability to define phenomena and make it act in a desired manner.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:24.000
And when they define that phenomena, the racist brutality in Black communities, in Oakland and L.A. have historical, have a track record of historical racism and brutal treatment of Black and Latino people.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:41.000
And in Oakland, in the 50s and 60s, it was routine for a Black man to get shot or a Black woman to get shot and by police over minor incidents, a traffic incident or something, where cops would just unleash their brutality.

01:07:41.000 --> 01:07:53.000
And so when Huey and Bobby were first organized in the party, one, they armed themselves with the law. They understood that it's interesting that this gun debate going on now.

01:07:53.000 --> 01:08:03.000
And of course this was at a time when there wasn't proliferation of guns in communities, let alone among kids in gangs now today.

01:08:03.000 --> 01:08:23.000
But when we were upholding the constitutional right to own and bear arms, the gun lobby today, the NRA, opposed panthers, owning guns, it's not surprising that, of course, they've done the 360 now today and they want all the guns they can get.

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:40.000
But at that time, we knew that we had the Constitution on our side, Huey and Bobby did. They also studied the California Penal Code and understood that legally that they had the right to carry arms and they had the right to observe police carrying out their duty.

01:08:40.000 --> 01:08:52.000
So they put those two together. They had also one of the readings that they often read was the Red Book by Chairman Mao Zedong about revolutionary theory and practicing.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:09:09.000
And so when they organized the first program, the police alert patrol, when they marched out on that street and faced down those cops on the Saturday night in Oakland with six or seven panthers with shotguns armed on the corner telling them they weren't going to brutalize that young man.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:26.000
That was really kind of the birth of the panther, mystique and the creation of the myth, if you will, Huey became almost a mythical figure from this. He was the one that led this incident.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:42.000
When the police officer told him, what are you doing with that gun, nigga, give me that gun and Huey jacked around into the chamber of his shotgun and said, this is my weapon, I have a right to carry this weapon if you attempt to take it away from him, I'm going to defend myself.

01:09:42.000 --> 01:10:07.000
And it was that moment that really captured the imagination of those people in Oakland. And so the downside to that was that because we were called the Black Panther Party for self-defense, people began to see the party as their own community defense force.

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:35.000
So that meant go get the panthers to do this or go get the panthers to do that. And that was not what we were about. We were setting the example that you had the right to defend yourself in your community and not have to take people brutalizing you unnecessarily illegally, unlawfully, through racist attack, but you had the right to stand up and defend yourself and stand up like a man.

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:55.000
And that was the message that we were sending, that the party was sending very early. Well, that's initially what put the bulls eye on our back. But as long as it was a localized organization in California, they didn't get a lot of attention.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:12.000
You know, the FBI probably thought that that would go away. But when this migration happened, and we were the first chapter, as I said outside of the state of California, it became clear that this was going to be something that they were going to have to deal with.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:30.000
So the 10th point platform and program really was about the basic needs of people within our community. I don't know if I can read all of this, but talk about what we want and what we believe, and I can summarize what the points were.

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:44.000
We wanted the end to the racist brutality of police within our community. We wanted an education that represented the true nature of black people.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:57.000
We wanted an end to the robbery of our communities by what we called then the avaricious business man who took resources out of the community and never gave anything back.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:07.000
We wanted healthcare, food, land, housing, education, justice and peace kind of summarized it all together. We wanted black men exempt from serving in military service.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:22.000
We wanted an end to all white juries trying blacks in the court when in fact they're guaranteed by the Constitution. They have a jury of their peers. Those were the elements of the 10 point program.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:34.000
When he broke that down to us, it really established what we were about, that we were going, these were the things that we were going to pursue.

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:50.000
It was going to take a lot of organizing. We had to, because we had a bullseye on our back, we had to eat every panther, had to own two guns and a thousand rounds of ammunition and be prepared to defend yourself because you would be under attack.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:13:02.000
We had to read two hours of day, two hours a day to educate ourselves and understand the concepts and theories of revolution and what it meant to be an organizer on a leader.

01:13:02.000 --> 01:13:24.000
We were basically preparing ourselves in those early years to become full blooded revolutionaries that stood for something and it had a revolutionary philosophy and developed the tools that we needed to become revolutionary practitioners.

01:13:24.000 --> 01:13:40.000
This meant that we had to basically, we were given our lives to this. When the reality set in of the seriousness of it, we had the same phenomenon that happened in Oakland, happened here in Seattle.

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:52.000
When Bobby Hutton was murdered in Seattle, a thousand people in the community joined the Black Panther Party overnight. It just exploded overnight.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:14:10.000
When we began to organize here in Seattle within a couple of weeks, we had 400-500 panthers that we were trying to organize and get into some sort of a disciplined structure.

01:14:10.000 --> 01:14:30.000
A lot of people joined the Panther Party because the end thing to do was not the right word, but it was a source of pride and a source of belonging, source of identity.

01:14:30.000 --> 01:14:44.000
This was during the turbulent 60s and people wanted direction, but most people didn't really understand what it meant to create a revolutionary movement.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:15:04.000
A lot of people in the Black community across the country were used to spontaneous rebellions. Our movement wasn't about a spontaneous rebellion. We were trying to build a political power structure that could challenge the status quo here in the United States.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:18.000
We had to set out built coalitions and gather resources and we had to know what it was that we were doing. That took time and effort and commitment.

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:34.000
It was clear that this was going to take, talk about reading two hours a day. I remember when I first picked up Richard of the Earth and my friends were gone, I thought, how do I understand this?

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:47.000
We had political education classes every day, not every day, but weekly. We would talk about what we read and get an understanding of what other revolutionary movements were about.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:16:00.000
We began to realize that it was going to take effort in order to build this coalition and build this foundation.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:27.000
Within six to twelve months, most of those panthers that came that first few weeks were gone, which was probably the best because we boiled down to a hardcore group of panthers, probably about 20, that we knew that we could count on not just for the glory.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:48.000
We buried two, maybe three panthers here in Seattle. One of them, I think it was either Butch Arms Ditz or Henry Boyer's funeral, was the largest at the time, the largest funeral in the state.

01:16:48.000 --> 01:17:08.000
Thousands of people attended and the panthers were all out in our leather jackets and berets and powder blue shirts and lining the streets in front of the mortuary.

01:17:08.000 --> 01:17:21.000
The guys that put on this uniform and women, but the guys, it was like this macho thing, it was a source of pride, but it was also a panther.

01:17:21.000 --> 01:17:35.000
We had to create this discipline to organization. It wasn't about just wearing the uniform and walking down the street and getting girls because you had a panther uniform on.

01:18:05.000 --> 01:18:13.000
That difficult process, I would imagine a difficult process of boiling down and the expulsions and the infighting.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:21.000
What was that like since you were trying to do something for yourself, for your community to experience that?

01:18:21.000 --> 01:18:45.000
I think we understood that that was going to be a natural part of the process. Any time when you are organizing something that is so involved and demanding of you as an individual, you know that there's going to be people that are not going to be able to adapt to that kind of a structure.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:59.000
It takes a certain person to be able to give of themselves completely and fall into this discipline body, this discipline to organization.

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:13.000
We were like a small army and so it required that you gave of yourself. It wasn't like some organizations that were like where you have this hierarchy and there's this submission.

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:24.000
It wasn't like that at all. It was more like a family and you had to have this close-knit family, but to go through the growing pains to get to that point, we realized it was going to be tough and it was tough as we went through it.

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:31.000
But I think that we understood there's a core of us that understood what the party meant and what it stood for.

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:42.000
And so we were going to do whatever it took to make sure that we came away with something that was going to be meaningful and make a difference and have an impact because we're putting our lives out there on the line.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:49.000
Just because we began to do this community organizing didn't take the bulls eye off our back and increased it.

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:57.000
In fact, we were a memo from our headquarters that said that leadership had to have two bodyguards. I had two bodyguards when I was 17 and 18 years old.

01:19:57.000 --> 01:20:03.000
And because we understood the seriousness of it.

01:20:03.000 --> 01:20:08.000
And so did you move out on your own at that point or were you living at home?

01:20:08.000 --> 01:20:21.000
I left that summer and moved out on my own. In fact, that was in April of 1968.

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:28.000
I graduated from Garfield in June of 1968. By the end of June I was out in my own apartment.

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:44.000
And Aaron was already out. And it was, you know, in those early days when I was still at my parents' house, my bodyguard would come home with me at night and sit on my front porch.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:53.000
And I wake up and wake up in the morning. He's still sitting there. And, you know, I told you, you can go home. I can, you know, take care of myself.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:21:01.000
But my parents would get calls in the middle of the night. My mother would answer the phone and somebody would say, we're going to kill that nigger son of yours tonight.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:12.000
And she would say, go ahead and try. Because, you know, she knew that I could take care of myself and she knew and Aaron could take care of himself. And she knew that we also had, you know, people that were standing at our side.

01:21:12.000 --> 01:21:19.000
And those were some of the things that my parents went through early on in those years. My father was visited as a job by the FBI.

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:27.000
You asked me earlier about him having to navigate Boeing. I don't remember. Like I said, I don't think he had to navigate Boeing so much. They were glad to have him.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:39.000
But it was when we became a politicized that the FBI's interest peeked up. Here he is working on, you know, in a manufacturing plant that had government contracts.

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:53.000
And so he caught some heat behind that. But, you know, going through these growing pains, you know, yes, it was painful. But at the same time, we knew it was necessary for us to, in order to evolve to where we wanted to.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:59.000
When we started our first free breakfast program in a church around the corner from my parents home.

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:11.000
It was a church that I had been a member of the Boy Scouts in, you know, and the pastor, quite naturally said, yes, while other churches turned us down.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:19.000
This was a white pastor who said, yes, black churches told us no. This white pastor told us, yes.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:31.000
It was because of that relationship that we had. And we realized that we had members of the party who we had a Japanese panther here, and a couple of Japanese panthers here in Seattle.

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:43.000
And while whites could not join the organization, our lawyers were considered kind of an extension of who we were. We had several white lawyers that were defending us in court.

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:57.000
And when you began to realize and understand the philosophy of the Black Panther Party, I remember a three chapters in the Black Panther Party became targets immediately in 1968.

01:22:57.000 --> 01:23:07.000
When J. Edgar Hoover put out the memo to destroy, disrupt and discredit the Black Panther Party by any means necessary out to his field offices.

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:17.000
They targeted three offices that they wanted to shut down. In fact, in the memo he said, present, prevent the rise of a Black Messiah".

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:25.000
And the three offices that he targeted were Los Angeles, Chicago, and Seattle.

01:23:25.000 --> 01:23:34.000
They already had the Bullseye on national headquarters in Oakland. And they had already got Huey was in jail at the time.

01:23:34.000 --> 01:23:49.000
So they already effectively pulled who they thought was the primary leader of the party out of the party. And Huey was locked up as a result of a gun battle he had with police where he was supposed to be killed.

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:59.000
But he was shot, but he ended up killing one police officer and wounding the other. And so they had him off the street.

01:23:59.000 --> 01:24:16.000
But L.A., Chicago and Seattle were problematic for the FBI and their eyes because in Los Angeles, you had a,

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:43.000
the leader of the Black Panther Party, they're a bunchie Carter, who was the former head of the largest gang in Los Angeles, the Slausons and 5,000 members strong to have him as head of the Los Angeles chapter of the Black Panther Party and organizing, you know, 5,000 gang members, let alone a truce between the other gangs was very problematic for the FBI.

01:24:43.000 --> 01:25:06.000
In Chicago, you had the same thing where Fred Hampton was organizing not only the Black gangs in Chicago, the (Gangster) Disciples, the Blackstone Rangers, but also, you know, getting the truce between them, but also organizing young whites and young Latinos.

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:28.000
And in Seattle, we had this broad coalition of Asians, of Latinos, of whites. And plus, here we were a little spot in the Northwest. A lot of people didn't know where Seattle was. But if we had had a major impact, then I guess that would have been problematic for them.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:49.000
So they targeted those three offices and with the idea of assassinating the leaders in those three chapters. A bunchie Carter was assassinated in Oakland, excuse me, in Los Angeles, Fred Hampton, you're probably aware of his assassination in Chicago. And they had several attempts on Aaron in my life, Aaron here in Seattle.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:26:06.000
On one such attempt, Aaron, I used to run the target practice for Panthers once a weekend out at a target range that we had set up. And on one particular Saturday, I didn't go out with Aaron to the target range.

01:26:06.000 --> 01:26:18.000
And Aaron had gone out with a group of Panthers. And as he prepared the fire as his shotgun, he at first was going to fire it from his shoulder.

01:26:18.000 --> 01:26:32.000
And he decided the last minute he was going to try hip fire and brought it down to his hip and the shotgun exploded. And it tore into his arm. He almost lost his arm. Of course, had he fired from his shoulder, he would have blown his head off.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:42.000
And we knew that someone had doctored with his ammunition. And there were other attempts on he and I's life in those years.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:27:02.000
But something that Fred Hampton said in 68 at a large rally. And in fact, there's a video out about Fred Hampton and his death. And this speech is on there where he says that he's talking to this large group on the South side of Chicago.

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:13.000
In fact, he's on the West side of Chicago in a church. And there's white students in there. There's Latino students in there probably Asian a lot of black people in there.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:30.000
What he said to them was that the reason why we say all power to the people, what we mean when we say all power to the people is that we mean that there should be white power for white people, brown power for brown people, yellow power for yellow people, red power for red people and black power for black people, all power to the people.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:44.000
And what we need is a rainbow coalition. And he coined that phrase, not Jesse Jackson. It came out of Fred Hampton's mouth first. And so we had always from the beginning. That was in 1968.

01:27:44.000 --> 01:28:10.000
And so we had a philosophy around what we call revolutionary revolutionary intercommunalism. And so we had branches of the Black Panther Party in BPP international branches, in BPP international branches, in BPP international branches, in BPP international branches, in BPP international branches.

01:28:10.000 --> 01:28:28.000
We had coalitions here in the United States with the Peace and Freedom Party, SDS, the Young Lords, a Puerto Rican group, the Red Guard, American Indian Movement.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:40.000
We had coalitions with all of these organizations. And while we discourage them from trying to join the Black Panther Party, we encourage them to organize within their own communities.

01:28:40.000 --> 01:28:52.000
So we had this natural network and coalition that was really about a multicultural foundation to the Black Panther Party.

01:28:52.000 --> 01:29:14.000
And most people don't realize that they don't know the history of the Black Panther Party. And so when I did that speech in France a few years ago on from revolutionary to interculturalist, we had always been interculturalists in the Black Panther Party.

01:29:14.000 --> 01:29:28.000
But my upbringing had always been multicultural. So it's like a full circle in my life. And for me personally that began with the influences of my parents and where they had positioned us.

01:29:28.000 --> 01:29:42.000
So we went on to organize the chapter. We ended up with five breakfast programs where we fed over 2,000 kids, a hot meal every morning before they went to school. And our breakfast programs were strategically located in housing projects around the city.

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:54.000
Four of the housing projects, all four of the housing projects, Yesler Terrace, Holly Park, High Point, Rainier Vista, and then one at the Atlantic Street Center, which had a more central location.

01:29:54.000 --> 01:30:09.000
We moved it out of the church and into, and oddly enough, the Atlantic Street Center was the very first neighborhood community center that we hang out in.

01:30:09.000 --> 01:30:23.000
When we moved here from Chicago in 1957, the very first one. And the head of that organization at the time was a gentleman by the name of Ike Ikeda.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:33.000
And Ike knew us when we were kids. And we went down there to ask him if we could have the breakfast program there. It was a natural response, of course.

01:30:33.000 --> 01:30:53.000
And so it was that kind of coalition that we had across the city and all of these different neighborhoods. We had white liberals, wealthy, some white wealthy liberals that were supporters of ours in those early years and continued to support us throughout the years.

01:30:53.000 --> 01:31:06.000
And even after the party went away, when we've done various events. But that foundation, that coalition that we built sustained us through those years.

01:31:06.000 --> 01:31:16.000
Because when the chapter shrunk down to us, a core member of people, we were probably more effective than we would have been with this large group.

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:26.000
Because we utilized the networks and the coalitions to host things and to get our word out and to build our programs.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:42.000
In fact, during the peace marches, the anti-war demonstrations, there was a doctor by the name of John Green, who was a neurologist at the University of Washington Medical School,

01:31:42.000 --> 01:32:06.000
who had put together a band of medical students and a medical detail that followed the demonstrators who were marching. And on the front lines, when someone got billy clubbed or tear gas, they would bring them to the back of these huge marches and they would be administered health care to.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:22.000
Well, we approached John about a free medical clinic. And he was all gun hole and told us how we needed. And it's actually our second headquarters.

01:32:22.000 --> 01:32:40.000
Because the first headquarters, the real headquarters, we had an office prior to there. Probably one of our most notorious headquarters was up on 34th and union, which ironically was around the corner from my parents house right there in Madrona.

01:32:40.000 --> 01:33:00.000
And the building is still there. But that was the first kind of notorious Panther office. But when we moved out of there in 1969, the fall of 1969, it was because of the attacks that were happening on party offices around the country.

01:33:00.000 --> 01:33:18.000
And so we were ordered into not only a more secure offices, but barracks. So the building that we got was a duplex. Downstairs was the offices and upstairs were the Panther barracks.

01:33:18.000 --> 01:33:41.000
And we had eventually two or three of those kind of buildings around the city, around the central area. And so our primary building was there on 20th and spruce. And in fact, the people's wall, we had an artist paint a wall around the building, which is still there.

01:33:41.000 --> 01:33:53.000
I don't know. You may want to go film that before you leave. It's on the corner of 20th and spruce. We had it refurbished about five years ago on our 40th anniversary.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:34:10.000
But that was the office where we began to fortify the office. We had sandbags on all the walls. We had bunkers inside for gun bunkers. We had steel and plywood sandwiches on the window. And that was the first side of our free medical clinic.

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:33.000
And Dr. Green set up the clinic in the back of the office. And he appropriated what we needed from the University of Washington. And he told us to back up a truck up to the hospital. He put in exam tables and medicine cabinets for the medications and equipment that he would need. And he just loaded this up.

01:34:33.000 --> 01:34:43.000
And we established our first clinic there. He went actually on to open four other neighborhood clinics in the Seattle area, assist with opening those clinics.

01:34:43.000 --> 01:34:51.000
But so our first free clinic was there put together by John Green. But the patients when they came into the clinic.

01:34:51.000 --> 01:35:05.000
And our first service was a well baby clinic for young mothers to address the infant mortality rate was very high among in the black community in those years. And so that was our first concentration.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:16.000
And when the pregnant mothers would come in, they would walk by, of course, the officer of the day. That was the office when you came in through the door that was about this thick.

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:29.000
And it was always guarded with an armed guard. They would walk in and then buy the sandbags and, well, it's under the, along the bunker and then back into the medical clinic to get their medical care.

01:35:29.000 --> 01:35:40.000
And people always said they felt secure when they walked in there. It wasn't like they were fearful of these sandbags. But they knew who we were. They knew that we were offering a free medical clinic and people came.

01:35:40.000 --> 01:35:49.000
And that was the birth of the, our first free medical clinic. And by the way, the Panther Clinic is still operating today. Carolyn Downs Family Medical Center.

01:35:49.000 --> 01:36:01.000
Carolyn was a young woman who worked with us in the, in the 70s and died when she was before she was 30, I believe.

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:17.000
In 1978, we were no longer the chapter by then, but we continued the efforts of the organization. So we probably had over 30 programs that we had organized both here and around the country, the other chapters and branches.

01:36:17.000 --> 01:36:30.000
We had the Free Busing to Prisons Program. We had a free food program, which was some of the, some of the first free food banks here in the area. We had the free shoe program, a free legal aid program, a free busing depresence program.

01:36:30.000 --> 01:36:48.000
We had that senior aid, legal aid, and then our summer liberation school, which was the foundation for creating what they did at Central Headquarters in Oakland, the Oakland Community Learning Center.

01:36:48.000 --> 01:37:12.000
My brother Aaron was transferred out of the chapter as was the whole chapter was transferred out of Seattle in 1971. And I was serving time in a prison in Oregon for allegedly stealing a litur of coat while I was down speaking on the campus at Oregon, or the University of Oregon and Eugene Oregon.

01:37:12.000 --> 01:37:41.000
And I spent 14 months in prison in Salem, Oregon as a political prisoner. And I remember hearing about some of the efforts that were going on when I was locked up, my parents, my father, and my brother had organized a meeting with the governor of Oregon at the time who was a very progressive and liberal governor, Governor Tom McCall.

01:37:42.000 --> 01:38:11.000
And they had arranged for a clemency hearing. And I didn't know really how to respond to that because I was a, you know, a died in the wall revolutionary at that point. And any concession was not within my power to give, nor was I going to give it, and appeared to be in collaboration with quote unquote the enemy.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:40.000
I had been subpoenaed before, before I was locked up in 1970 before the House Un-American Activities Committee. And the reason why they subpoenaed me was because when they sent their congressional investigator out to find cooperative or cooperative witnesses, Aaron instructed me to talk to the investigator.

01:38:40.000 --> 01:39:07.000
And he asked me, one of the things he asked me was, why do you, you know, feed kids a hot breakfast? And I said, you know, look, how are you going to ask kids to go to school that are hungry and ask them to learn in a classroom where they're comparing, you know, apples, you know, two apples plus four apples equals six apples, you know, expect their stomach to grumble how they're going to focus and concentrate them, you know, make sense to give them nutritional breakfast.

01:39:07.000 --> 01:39:34.000
And so when I explained our programs and you know, why the free medical, etc. So he took that to mean that I was a cooperative witness, but I was, you know, basically instructed to explain to him why we had these programs. And so when I was subpoenaed, you know, I was told that, you know, if you get in there, you know, this is the House Un-American Activities Committee.

01:39:34.000 --> 01:39:46.000
So I knew that with my lawyers instructed us that, you know, you can answer, you instructed me that I can answer my name and where I lived and what my occupation was.

01:39:47.000 --> 01:39:59.000
Anything after that would compel you to answer. So after I gave them those three things, I told them at the very next question was, are you a member of the Black Panther Party?

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:20.000
And I said, I refused to answer on the grounds of self-incrimination, I take the Fifth Amendment. And with each question, they got, they grew more and more angry. It was, it's kind of like the Nikita Khrushchev bouncing his, his hand is a chew on the table. They were just so infuriated that, that now they had flown me all the way to D.C., and I wasn't a cooperative witness.

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:39.000
And so I knew, you know, I mean, the, we were on one side and the government was on the other. So while I was in prison in 71, Attica erupted. And, you know, and George Jackson, who was a member of the Black Panther Party, was murdered in San Quentin.

01:40:39.000 --> 01:40:50.000
And after Attica, the, the captain of the prison called me and another Panther, who was from the Portland chapter.

01:40:51.000 --> 01:41:06.000
Williams, red Williams called him in the, the two of us into the office, his office and told us that if anything broke out in, in their prison, they were going to shoot us first.

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:18.000
And so we knew that we were, you know, still even in prison, you know, the, you know, the, the targets. And so when the, the governor's office came to the prison.

01:41:19.000 --> 01:41:28.000
And the, the, the investigator said he was there to, you know, to, for a clemency hearing to pursue, clemency that the governor wanted to pursue clemency.

01:41:28.000 --> 01:41:35.000
I, my response to him was the only thing that I like, you tell the governor that the only thing that I'll accept from him is an unconditional surrender.

01:41:36.000 --> 01:41:38.000
And he said, God, it was funny.

01:41:39.000 --> 01:41:40.000
Anyway, this is good.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:45.000
We're trying to get you out of prison, but I didn't want to get out under those circumstances.

01:41:46.000 --> 01:41:53.000
And so while I was there, the chapter was, was literally closed in Seattle. Everybody was transferred to Oakland.

01:41:53.000 --> 01:41:57.000
And were you, were you organizing while you were incarcerated?

01:41:58.000 --> 01:42:03.000
Oh, yeah. Well, there was, you know, there were, there was at least three other panthers in, in, in that, in that prison.

01:42:04.000 --> 01:42:10.000
They were, or, Oregon panthers in myself. And, you know, we had to do subtle things around the organizing.

01:42:11.000 --> 01:42:18.000
You know, we'd meet, we'd had political, political education classes. There wasn't much more we could do other than keep ourselves abreast of what was going on.

01:42:18.000 --> 01:42:25.000
You know, and being aware of and not letting someone get, get, get, take an advantage of in the prison. Protect ourselves while we're in prison.

01:42:26.000 --> 01:42:31.000
And so it wasn't the same kind level of organizing we would obviously do on the outside.

01:42:32.000 --> 01:42:35.000
You know, the Oregon prisons are not what you would find in like a California prison, obviously.

01:42:36.000 --> 01:42:45.000
Where, where political organizing, there was a, it was a hotbed up, it was, it was a need to do that kind of political organizing in San Quentin or in, in Soledad.

01:42:45.000 --> 01:42:52.000
Oregon prison, you know, it was not nearly the, the platform for that kind of thing.

01:42:53.000 --> 01:42:57.000
So we could keep ourselves abreast of what was going on. But there wasn't a need for this kind of broad organization.

01:42:58.000 --> 01:43:01.000
There weren't like gang war fears inside prisons, you know, that kind of thing.

01:43:02.000 --> 01:43:14.000
Which George Jackson was like, was, was, was beginning to form a coalition between the, he, he organized the, the Latino prisoners and the, and the black prisoners and, you know, in, in San Quentin and Soledad.

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:21.000
But we didn't have that opportunity in the prison that I was in. So it was much more low key in that way.

01:43:22.000 --> 01:43:34.000
But by the time I got out, I was paroled in, in, in late 72, the chapter, there was a group of community workers that were still there.

01:43:35.000 --> 01:43:44.000
They had moved into a new building, the old office with all the sandbags was gone. And you could see kind of the shift in the era, you know, from those early years.

01:43:45.000 --> 01:43:58.000
And the party to now just a few short years later, where, you know, the sandbags were gone. You know, we weren't sleeping with guns underneath our pillows. And, you know, it was, it was, it was a very different time.

01:43:59.000 --> 01:44:07.000
But we still went around, went about the, the, the business of organizing the community. And that meant through, you know, organizing our survival programs.

01:44:07.000 --> 01:44:19.000
And so the clinic was now in another building in the offices that we had now. No one, we, while we did have a 24 hour guard, someone had to be at the building at 24 hours at all times.

01:44:20.000 --> 01:44:25.000
We, no one, you know, lived there. And can I ask you about it?

01:44:25.000 --> 01:44:41.000
I can't ask you about it. Because it's either, well, I was going to ask you because there's the, the, the famous sort of split, right? And, whereas it's sometimes called within the panthers about, you know, do we continue this sort of militarism in the gorilla revolution?

01:44:42.000 --> 01:44:45.000
Yeah. Or focus on survival programs and meeting the basic needs of black people.

01:44:45.000 --> 01:44:55.000
But it sounds like your description of what happened in Seattle. There's, there's still kind of a mix of the two. Or how did you see it playing out?

01:44:56.000 --> 01:44:58.000
Well, there was that mix of the two. There was mixes too. I probably in every chapter.

01:44:59.000 --> 01:45:12.000
We had that kind of many split, if you will, in our chapter early on. And probably early 1969.

01:45:12.000 --> 01:45:29.000
And, you know, there was, there was, in fact, he was our brother-in-law, who had more of a military, you know, let's, you know, do it now kind of a mentality.

01:45:29.000 --> 01:45:50.000
And did some things that were, some things that were kind of contrary to what we were about. And what we considered to be, you know, like sensationalizing, you know, sensationalism.

01:45:50.000 --> 01:46:03.000
And so there was that ideological split here in Seattle. But what they faded, in fact, several of them went to prison for a bank robbery.

01:46:04.000 --> 01:46:07.000
Others kind of just faded in.

01:46:07.000 --> 01:46:16.000
And it was a little more involved than, you know, I'm not going to name names. But, but that split occurred.

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:26.000
We maintained control of the organization and continued to build the structure that Huey and Bobby wanted in the first place.

01:46:26.000 --> 01:46:40.000
That the big ideological split on the national level was really perpetuated by informants in the FBI through COINTELPRO.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:48.000
You know, it wasn't just about assassinating leaders because they could only get so many of these.

01:46:48.000 --> 01:46:53.000
Blue a couple of opportunities here. And then we're going to get that opportunity again.

01:46:54.000 --> 01:46:56.000
Can you define what that is just for?

01:46:57.000 --> 01:46:58.000
COINTELPRO.

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:11.000
COINTELPRO is a program actually put together over way back in the early 20s and 2001.

01:47:11.000 --> 01:47:22.000
He was assumed with the idea that the Communists wanted to take over the United States and the Communist threat.

01:47:23.000 --> 01:47:26.000
And so COINTELPRO was an acronym for counterintelligence.

01:47:28.000 --> 01:47:32.000
So he went with a spine and eventually tapping.

01:47:32.000 --> 01:47:44.000
And it was active, you know, all through the union busting years in the 40s, you know, breaking up the unions during the McCarthy.

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:59.000
When they went on the witch hunt and blacklisted top actors from Hollywood on into the civil rights movement when they wiretapped Martin Luther King and wiretapping these.

01:47:59.000 --> 01:48:08.000
And so it kind of evolved into when the party already emerged.

01:48:09.000 --> 01:48:17.000
It was the new threat that they saw as a bigger threat even than King.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:28.000
And so all of it's the COINTELPRO's energies now were directed towards revelations across the United States.

01:48:29.000 --> 01:48:34.000
And the Panthers were at the top of the list. That's why he declared the party the number one.
